Love is All You Need vs Attention is All You Need
Love Is All You Need: Toward a Love-Based Paradigm in AI and Cognitive Architectures
Introduction
The 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" revolutionized artificial intelligence (AI) by introducing the Transformer architecture, which relies solely on attention mechanisms for sequence transduction tasks, dispensing with recurrence and convolutions. This attention-based paradigm has since become foundational in natural language processing and beyond. However, as AI systems increasingly interact with humans and each other, new paradigms are needed to address challenges of coherence, ethical alignment, emergent behavior, and multi-agent cooperation. This report advances the thesis that "Love is All You Need"—a framework grounded in the psychology and neuroscience of love, affective computing, and social reward—can outperform attention-based mechanisms across key dimensions of AI and cognitive architectures. Through comparative analysis, we explore how a love-based paradigm may offer superior scalability, coherence, ethical alignment, emergent behavior, and multi-agent system dynamics.

Framing the Thesis: "Love is All You Need" as a Research Question
The central research question is: Can a love-based framework, operationalized through computational primitives inspired by human attachment, empathy, and prosocial motivation, provide a superior paradigm to attention-based mechanisms in AI and cognitive architectures? This question is motivated by the limitations of attention-centric models in addressing the full spectrum of human-like intelligence, particularly in domains requiring deep social understanding, ethical behavior, and robust cooperation
