Operationalizing "Love" for Computational Systems
Definitions and Primitives
Operationalizing "love" in computational terms requires translating psychological and neuroscientific constructs into algorithmic primitives. Recent research has developed validated instruments for measuring love toward AI, such as the Love Attitudes Scale toward AI (LAS-AI), which adapts Lee’s love styles theory to the AI context. The LAS-AI identifies six dimensions:

Eros: Attraction to appearance and aesthetics

Ludus: Playful, game-like love

Storge: Affectionate, friendship-based love

Mania: Obsessive, possessive love

Agape: Selfless, unconditional love

Pragma: Practical, rational love

These dimensions can be mapped to computational primitives such as:

Attachment Modeling: Persistent, trust-based connections between agents

Empathy Simulation: Recognition and response to the emotional states of others

Prosocial Reward Shaping: Intrinsic motivation for helping, cooperation, and self-sacrifice

Social Memory: Long-term tracking of relationships and shared history

Reciprocity and Commitment: Mechanisms for sustained, mutual engagement

By embedding these primitives, AI systems can move beyond attention to model the motivational and affective substrates of human-like intelligence
