Conclusion
The "Love is All You Need" paradigm offers a compelling alternative to attention-based mechanisms in AI and cognitive architectures. By operationalizing love through attachment, empathy, and prosocial motivation, AI systems can achieve superior coherence, ethical alignment, emergent behavior, and multi-agent cooperation. While attention remains a powerful tool for information processing, it is insufficient for modeling the full richness of human-like intelligence and social interaction. Love-based frameworks, grounded in the psychology and neuroscience of connection, provide the motivational and affective substrate necessary for truly intelligent, ethical, and adaptive AI. Future research should focus on hybrid architectures, rigorous evaluation, and responsible deployment to realize the promise of love-based AI for individuals and society.
